<TITLE> Official swine flu count rises to 259 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 2 (bdnews24.com)--The official count of people infected with swine flu reached 259 after twelve more fresh cases were detected on Wednesday, the IEDCR director said. "The counting is not necessary now," Dr Mahmudur Rahman told bdnews24.com. "One will have to take physician's advice and take cautionary measures after the symptoms are noticed," he said. "We are making arrangement to prevent the disease and handle it," he added. According to experts, Bangladesh has already crossed danger level 2. Though it has not turned to an epidemic the situation is not far off. The World Health Organisation declared swine flu pandemic on June 11. As many as 2,185 people have died from the H1N1 virus so far. Over 20 lakh people were detected with the virus. The symptom of swine flu is high fever with respiratory problems and coughs. Experts suggested people refrain from splitting here and there, and wash hands with soaps for at least 20 seconds after sneezing to curb spread of the H1N1 virus. The deadly virus was first detected in Mexico in April but Bangladesh reported its first case in June. The government on Monday confirmed the first H1N1 death in Bangladesh. Doctors at Lab Aid Hospital in Dhaka said the victim was a 35-year old woman Mitali Chakravarty of Savar died at around 10.30pm on Sunday. bd
